<br>
The difference is knowing where to draw a line in the sand - and most parents are unwilling to make that line and instead keep their children out of EVERYTHING for fear of Child Protective Services.  Maybe letting little Billy run around means he makes a mistake and breaks his arm.  You can bet damn sure he learned what he shouldn't do.  This isn't to say I want any child to break their arm, but some mistakes have to be learned <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>from</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> not of.<br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong, I think CPS are great when used properly.  Abused, ignored, or improperly-cared for children need to be in loving environments, but some parents just need to stand up and say &quot;Billy, you do drugs, and I'm gonna make you wish you'd never been born&quot; and be willing to enforce it.  It's all about balance - don't give them a mile, but give them an inch.  Parents that kick kids out are just as responsible as parents who coddle.  And it is possible to be strict AND nurturing while still letting the kids make their own mistakes.  It's just a shame most parents don't seem to know how. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9AB3CA><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub238.ezboard.com/bthepowderroom77512.showUserPublicProfile?gid=danaere>Danaere</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://webpages.charter.net/elycion/images/smilies/heartbeat.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>TPR Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/5/03 3:51 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://p221.ezboard.com/fthepowderroom77512frm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=285.topic&index=18>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://webpages.charter.net/elycion/images/eeyore.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Ignorant People Annoy Me</span><hr size=1> My kids (so far, anyway) are what I would consider &quot;good kids&quot;. Nonetheless, they did manage to set their bedroom on fire a few months back. Luckily, we have smoke detectors, and my husband (who was home with them at the time) promptly investigated and dealt with it. In spite of that, there was damage to the floor, wall, and a piece of furniture. They were within 2 rooms and hearing distance the entire time, and had been out of line of sight less than 10 minutes.<br>
<br>
We all might hope that they made a mistake, and learned from it (playing with electrical outlets is bad, and can hurt you, and make fire, which is scary). However, based on the fact that my 2 year old STILL tries to pry the safety plugs out of the outlets on the wall, I'm guessing not. Guess what? I'm not gonna let him set his room on fire again just to see if he learns the second time around.<br>
<br>
I'm willing to let them take some bumps and bruises once in awhile to learn how their own actions can affect them. When they start a fistfight with each other, I often try to let it run it's course without interfering if possible. (My younger son is very sturdy and can hold his own against his older but skinnier brother.) But there's a point where it's not appropriate. I'm not going to let them play in the street until one of the maniac teenagers doing 45 through here hits them and then <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>hope</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> that all they have is a broken arm. Or the way my 4 year old likes to stand up and drop to his butt in the bathtub ... you'd think after he managed to hit his chin and have 7 stitches, perhaps he wouldn't think that was an ok game anymore? Well, no. Actually, he still does it when he can, and has taught his younger brother to do it as well. Clearly, some things need a bit more than just &quot;run amok, make mistakes, and learn from them&quot;. I have to nurture and protect them (even from themselves) until they some of their own reasoning and sense of self preservation kicks in. So at the ripe age of 2, I most certainly did NOT let my son climb to the very highest point on the jungle gym when he wanted to. 18 months later, I shrugged and let him try. <br>
<br>
